ARNOLD

Where the moon-silvered inlets Send far their light voice

Up the still vale of Thisbe,

O speed, and rejoice!

On the sward at the cliii-top Lie strewn the white flocks. On the cliff-side the pigeons Roost deep in the rocks.

In the moonlight the shepheffls, Soft luned by the rills,

Lie wrapt in their blankets Asleep on the hills.

——XVhat forms are these coming So white through the gloom? What garments out-glistening The gold-flowered broom?

What sweet-breathing presence Out-perfumes the thyme? What voices enrapture

The night's balmy prime ?—

’Tis Apollo comes leading His choir, the Nine. —The leader is fairest, But all are divine.

They are lost in the hollowsl They stream up again! What seeks on this mountain The glorified tulin?—
